The paper deals with online learning settings in which experts act strategically to maximize their influence on the learning algorithm's predictions by potentially misreporting their beliefs about a sequence of binary events. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The paper also aims to achieve no-regret and incentive compatibility, which are topics related to Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper proposes algorithms to achieve these goals, which involves designing efficient data structures and algorithms, making it relevant to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper also discusses the performance of the proposed algorithms in experiments, which involves analyzing the information-theoretic limits of the algorithms, making it relevant to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
